The 1033 Program Is Actually Pretty Boring
Sure, it gives local police armored vehicles and guns. But they mostly get printers and computer monitors.
By Lindsey Cook , Data Editor   Aug. 25, 2014
By Lindsey Cook , Data Editor   Aug. 25, 2014, at 1:35 p.m.
More
U.S. News & World Report

The 1033 Program Is Actually Pretty Boring
More
An older MRAP model designed for Iraq.

While media attention about the 1033 Program has focused on military vehicles and weapons – like this mine-resistant, armored-protective vehicle, known as an MRAP – many items procured are commonplace. Paul Shinkman for USNWR

When local law enforcement agencies in Ferguson, Missouri, approached protesters in what looked like military-style tanks , wearing riot gear and camo outfits, they started a national conversation about the militarization of police.

The Defense Department gives police surplus military equipment free of charge through the 1033 Program . The program opened to all departments with the National Defense Authorization Act for fiscal year 1997, and is tied to the war on drugs and the war on terror.

Criticism following Ferguson has centered on mine-resistant vehicles, weapons and other tactical equipment. But to many small police agencies that use the program, 1033 is more a way to get printers, desk chairs and other equipment that's needed yet not always in the budget.

“I watched the news last night and I am really concerned that the weapons portion of the program is going to get blown out of proportion,” says Chief Perry Waggener of the Reservoir Police in Ridgeland, Mississippi. “It concerns me because I would hate to see this program go away. It has a lot of benefits for my agency.”

Waggener’s department is a “special little” state agency that operates in five Mississippi counties. Through the program, it has gotten a response trailer with a generator, channel markers, a large boat, a barge, extension cords, life vests, ponchos, marine radios, computers, monitors and much more.

[ READ : Which States Use the 1033 Program More? ]

“The thing about the 1033 Program is, everything you can imagine, you can get. We have even gotten replacement light bulbs for our flashlights,” Waggener says. “Money is tight. Working within our budget, we can do more than we once could because of this program.”

An officer in the Sanford Police Department in Maine likens the program to eBay, from which police can get everything from toilet paper and underwear to printers and parts for their cars.

“[The public] thinks of the guns, the armored vehicle, the helicopter, but it’s really the small items that make an impact on the department,” says Sgt. Jason Wagner, who started as a point of contact for Maine’s program at the end of July.

Wagner’s first acquisition through the program consisted of “information centers” – devices that feature a copy machine, printer and scanner in one. He says his department didn’t have the budget to buy one of the machines at normal cost, and has been using them now for three years.

The department also used the program to outfit toolboxes, and now saves even more money by having staff do minor repairs to police vehicles with tools and parts obtained through 1033.

“A lot of people don't think about law enforcement tools being photocopier and fax machines and stuff like that, but that's what we need every day. But many times we can't afford those things because it isn't planned when something breaks to have the money to fix it," Wagner says.

The more boring pieces of equipment make up the bulk of transfers, says Mimi Schirmacher of the Defense Logistics Agency, which manages the program on a national level. Of the items the program provides, Schirmacher says 5 percent are weapons and less than 1 percent are tactical vehicles.

A state coordinator provided another measure, saying 55 percent of items in his database were non-military and 45 percent were military.

[ ALSO : Most Popular Items in the Defense Department's 1033 Program ]

The distinction is somewhat arbitrary and relates to how long the program coordinators track the items. Non-military items drop off the list after a year. Military items, such as utility trucks and night-vision goggles, are always leased and need to be transferred back to the national office or another department if they aren’t being used.

Local police departments pay for shipping an item and may pay a percentage of its value or a flat fee to participate in the program, depending on each state's rules. O btaining items needed for day-to-day tasks either free or at a drastically reduced cost means they can have more equipment for less and spend money on other needs.

“It could mean the difference on if someone gets overtime or if someone gets to keep their job,” says Craig Batzer, the program coordinator for Ohio.

Capt. Glenn Walton of the Odenville Police Department in Alabama says because of money saved through the program, his department was able to update its vehicles. All the equipment the department has received helps serve the rapidly growing community of Odenville.

When the department moved into a new office over a year ago, the entire office was furnished through the program. At an open house for the community, officials were able to point to the desks, computers and furniture and tell taxpayers that it didn’t cost them any extra.

“We made sure we told them, ‘Hey, you see this desk here? We got this from the surplus department. We got this free.’ They were very impressed,” Walton says.

The department also obtained Humvees through the program, which were critical in reaching citizens during two recent severe weather disasters in the town.

“Had we not had these vehicles, we would have been at the mercy of volunteers with four-wheel trucks,” Walton explains. “We are a real small city. Small cities have small budgets. [The program] gives us the tools we need to serve the community.”

